result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (2nd) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (2nd Offense), Requirement for Ignition Interlock Device] and Operating w/ PAC (2nd) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (2nd Offense), Requirement for Ignition Interlock Device]. The defendant was found guilty of OWI (2nd) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (2nd Offense), Requirement for Ignition Interlock Device] and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (2nd) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (2nd Offense), Requirement for Ignition Interlock Device] was dismissed by the court.

  • Benjamin Jermain Keppers was found guilty of OWI (2nd) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (2nd Offense), Requirement for Ignition Interlock Device], an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.
